{[%evp 0,40,24,26,27,-9,35,-29,-24,-31,0,-13,-32,-44,-30,-21,-10,-17,-17,-24,
-22,-14,-4,-3,18,10,3,2,2,-27,0,2,-2,-2,3,-4,-6,-6,-7,11,0,5,7]} 1. Nf3 d5 2.
g3 Nd7 {This is a move that has been always played now and then to only start
enjoy immense popularity since late 2019 when Alekseenko used it to beat
Karjakin in a very important game at Isle of Man, the game that yielded him a
spot in the Candidates. To be honest, it is also necessary to say it was
played before by many eminent GMs, such as Xiong and Vallejo Pons, but I
believe most strong players paid close attention to it only after that
aforementioned encounter between the two Russian players. What is the idea? We
simply want to continue with ...e7-e5!, reaching some Pirc position with
colours reversed. While it is clear that the setup with Nbd2 is by no means
the most ambitious one against the classical Pirc, the situation is different
when we are playing Black while also being a tempo down, as our ambitions are
limited to getting a very solid position - though, of course, we wouldn't mind
winning chances if the opportunity arises! At this point, White's main move by
far is 3.d4. However, such moves as 3.Bg2, ignoring Black's idea, as well as 3.
c4, trying to undermine the Black central pawn immediately, also need to be
addressed.} 3. c4 {This was tried by several good players, such as Artemiev,
Howell, Goganov, Van Foreest, etc. However, I believe we will get a good game
without much hassle.} dxc4 {Now we reach some fairly important crossroads.
White's main move has been 4.Qa4, but such ideas as 4.Na3, 4.Bg2 and 4.Qc2
have also been tried. It is important to understand that many of these moves
are likely to end up simply transposing to the main line, but we still need to
be aware of their existence as well as of the fact that White might try to get
something better than a mere transposition.} 4. Qa4 (4. Qc2 e5 $1 (4... e6 5.
Qxc4 a6 {And we have transposed to the line 4.Qa4 a6 5.Qxc4 e6.}) 5. Bg2 (5.
Qxc4 Ngf6 {Now White doesn't have a smarter move 6.Bg2, anyway.}) 5... Ngf6 6.
Qxc4 Bd6 7. O-O (7. d3 O-O 8. O-O {Transposes to 7.O-O.}) 7... O-O 8. d3 Re8 {
We have more space and a very comfortable development thanks to the awkward
position of the White queen on c4, as we can always gain the time with ideas
like ...Nb6, ...Be6 etc.}) (4. Na3 e5 $1 {The threat of ... Bxa3 forces White
to take on c4.} 5. Nxc4 e4 $1 6. Nd4 (6. Nh4 Nb6 $146 7. Ne3 (7. Nxb6 axb6 $17
{Just helps Black develop and should better be avoided.}) 7... Ne7 $5 {This
interesting move takes the f5-square under control and creates a sudden threat
of ...g7-g5! Now White does not have the time for Bg2, while after} 8. Qc2 $1
f5 9. b3 g5 $1 {We reach some really fun position, which is absolutely
unexplored.} 10. Bb2 Rg8 11. Nhg2 Be6 12. h4 h6 $15 {I like Black though, as
he has more space and White's g2-knight is clearly a rather ugly piece, isn't
it.}) 6... Nb6 7. e3 Nf6 8. Bg2 Bc5 9. Nb3 Be7 10. Ne5 c5 $17 {Obviously, the
White player is an extremely strong GM who understands chess very well, but
here it looks like he was having a bad day, as White's position after just 10
moves seems simply terrible.} 11. O-O O-O 12. f4 exf3 13. Qxf3 c4 14. Na5 Qc7
15. d4 cxd3 16. Nxd3 Rd8 $17 {I guess, we can stop here, as White has the
worse structure and the clearly worse pieces. The fact that he managed to save
the game has something to do with the moves that followed later, not with his
opening choice, which was clearly a disaster. 1/2 (46) Goganov,A (2635)
-Riazantsev,A (2651) Novosibirsk 2016}) (4. Bg2 e5 $1 {I think this is the
easiest solution, as well as the most ambitious one.} 5. Qa4 (5. O-O e4 $1 6.
Ne1 Ngf6 7. Qa4 {Suddenly, we transpose to a position from the next chapter,
covered under 2.g3 Nd7 3.Bg2 e5!}) 5... Bd6 6. Qxc4 {This is analyzed after 4.
Qc2.}) 4... a6 5. Qxc4 b5 (5... e6 {We now transpose to an interesting line 1.
c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3.g3 dxc4 4.Qa4+ Nd7 5.Qxc4 a6. I believe this variation is
harmless for Black, but it's worth knowing about the fact it can also arise
from a different move order, so that you can also hopefully use this line
against the Catalan. This is a perfectly valid way to play, but I think that
the immediate 5...b5, according to Caruana and many others, is the easiest
path. Feel free to study this as an alternative, though.}) 6. Qc2 {This is by
all means the main move.} (6. Qc6 {This was tried by an IM 2450 and by a few
other decent players, but after} Rb8 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. Qc2 {It is truly hard to
understand why provoking ...Rb8 can be any good for White, especially because .
..Rb8 comes as an extra tempo for us, for free!} c5 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg8f6,Gf8d6,
Ge8g8,Gh8f8] We will study similar positions in more detail in the main line,
so let's stop here.}) (6. Qb3 Bb7 7. Bg2 e6 8. O-O Ngf6 9. Nc3 (9. d3)) 6...
Bb7 7. Bg2 Ngf6 8. O-O e6 {Now Black simply wants to go ...c7-c5 and develop
his kingside. Usually a rule of thumb in such positions is that if we get to
play ...c7-c5 without any issues, our position is very comfortable.} (8... c5 {
Also looks completely fine, most likely it'll be a transposition.}) 9. a4 (9.
d3 {Is a move White can start with, but after} c5 10. a4 {We just transpose to
what we analyze via 9.a4 10.d3.}) (9. d4 $6 {This is definitely an
ambitious-looking move, but in fact, I am not sure at all if I like it! The
reason is that now, unlike in the positions with the pawn on d2, all this play
with ...Rc8 and ...c7-c5 starts making sense not only from the positional
perspective but also from the dynamic one as the White queen can prove rather
vulnerable!} c5 $1 10. a4 (10. dxc5 Bxc5 {We develop our bishop while also
winning a tempo.} 11. Nc3 Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c2] Now ...b5-b4 and ...Bxg2 is
hanging in the air.} 12. a3 O-O 13. Bg5 $6 {This is the most popular move, but
of course, I cannot approve of it, as after} h6 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 $17 {Black has a
clear advantage thanks to the bishop pair and the most active pieces.}) 10...
cxd4 {10...b5-b4 and 10...Rc8 also make perfect sense, but I go with the
easiest option.} 11. Nxd4 (11. axb5 $6 axb5 12. Rxa8 Qxa8 {And it's not that
easy to get the d4-pawn back because of the pressure over the long diagonal!})
11... Rc8 12. Qd1 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 b4 $5 {I think it's a good idea to take the
c3-square away from the White knight. This is clearly a move that is very
ambitious, and possibly risky, as if White gets to trade several pieces, keep
a knight vs our bishop and install that knight on c4, we might end up with
some very weak pawns. At the same time, it's important to understand there are
many factors involved, not just some potential endgame, and the extra space
also matters a lot, as well as activity! A good thing to mention is that
b2-b3? will almost always lead to a disaster because it weakens the c3-square
and enables ...Nd5-c3.} (13... Qb6 $11 {Is the more solid and peaceful choice.}
)) (9. b3 {White can definitely start in this way, too, but he'll need to play
d2-d3 and, likely, a2-a4 soon, which will transpose to 9.d3 or 9.a4.} c5 10.
Bb2 Be7 11. d3 O-O 12. Nbd2 Qb6 $132 {With a rich complex position where White
is rather flexible, while Black has more space. One good game to focus on here
is Sarana-Akobian.} 13. e4 Rfd8 14. Rac1 Rac8 15. Rfd1 Nb8 16. Ne5 Nfd7 17.
Nxd7 Rxd7 18. Nf3 Nc6 19. a3 Nd4 20. Nxd4 cxd4 $15 {0-1 (45) Sarana,A (2664)
-Akobian,V (2627) Saint Louis 2019}) 9... c5 10. d3 (10. Nc3 Qb6 11. d3 {
Is going to be a transposition to the main line. 1-0 (53) Aronian,L (2797)
-Wojtaszek,R (2744) Beijing 2014}) (10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 {For the sake
of clarity, let's assume we take with the bishop at all times to keep things
simple.} (11... Qxa8 {Is also a possible move, and a good one, which you can
investigate a bit more yourself.}) 12. Nc3 (12. Na3 Qb6 {Now White had tried
several moves, such as b2-b3, d2-d3, etc. In my opinion, none of those pose
problems, we just continue logically with the normal developing moves. But, I
want to mention one unexpected idea White might go for here.} 13. b4 $5 {
White's idea is to take on c5 and get a pawn structure where our b5-pawn might
prove either an asset or a weakness.} (13. Qb3 Bc6 {Transposes to the main
line.}) 13... Bb7 {We take the c8-square under control, threatening to take on
b4.} (13... cxb4 $2 14. Qc8+ Qd8 15. Qxd8+ Kxd8 16. Nxb5 $36 {Is not what we
need!}) 14. bxc5 Bxc5 15. Qb2 $5 {Immediately putting pressure on b5, until
it's too late, as if we castle and go Rb8, White is not getting anywhere.} Bc6
16. d3 O-O $132 {White did not create any problems, we are doing great here.})
12... Qb6 {We again transpose to the main line.}) 10... Be7 {We end up in a
popular theoretical position from the Anti-Catalan, where I think Black has no
reason to worry at all, as this move order is known to be harmless. Many games
have been played here, let's investigate some of the White's main
continuations.} 11. Nc3 Qb6 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 14. Qb3 Nd5 {This is
the easiest move, but other continuations are also very decent.} (14... b4 15.
Nd1 O-O 16. Ne3 Qa6 17. Nc4 h6 {This position is also completely acceptable as
the weakness of the c4-square is compensated by our extra space. However,
there is no need to go here, if you feel uncomfortable about the outpost on c4
that the White knight is fancying so much.}) 15. Bg5 (15. Nxb5 $2 Bc6 16. e4
N5f6 17. e5 Qxb5 (17... Nd5 $2 18. Nd6+ $1) 18. Qxb5 Bxb5 19. exf6 Bxf6 $15 {
With a clear positional advantage thanks to the better structure.}) (15. Qxb5
$4 Nxc3 16. Qxb6 Nxe2+ 17. Kh1 Nxb6 {And Black wins a piece.}) 15... Nxc3 16.
Qxc3 f6 $1 17. Bd2 O-O {This was seen in one game, between Aronian and
Wojtaszek. White won, but I think the opening outcome was convenient for us,
let's see how the game went and come up with an improvement for Black.} 18. Ra1
Bb7 19. Ne1 Kf7 $5 $146 {This move might look weird, but there are not too
many pieces on the board so the king is not going to be in any danger. However,
protecting the e6-pawn and approaching the center in the event of a possible
upcoming endgame seems very reasonable. It also does not make sense to take on
g2 and improve the White's knight on e1. For example, now after} (19... Bxg2
20. Nxg2 Qc6 21. Qb3 c4 $6 {This was not needed at all. Now Black has a
weakness, and while his position is not too bad objectively, White is clearly
somewhat better and later Levon went on to convert this position.} 22. dxc4
bxc4 23. Qc2 $14 {1-0 (53) Aronian, L (2797)-Wojtaszek,R (2744) Beijing 2014})
20. Bxb7 Qxb7 {Black wants to play . ..Rc8, ...Ne5-c6-d4. Another idea could
be to go ...Ra8 and swap the rooks. It is quite obvious we have no problems at
all here. If you doubt this conclusion, just look at the e1-knight and at the
amount of space both sides have!} *

