{[%evp 0,22,26,27,27,-9,48,6,4,-4,-11,-5,15,6,16,22,22,30,22,17,29,10,34,31,0]
} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nd7 3. Bg2 {One of the key questions is whether we get a
good position in the reversed Pirc. Let us investigate!} e5 {At this point,
White can play in different ways. The move 4.d3 is the main one by far, by
White can also castle, play 4.c4, or even 4.d4!} 4. d3 (4. O-O Ngf6 5. d3 {
This position is investigated via 4.d3 Ngf6 5.O-O.} (5. c4 {This is the only
independent possibility after 4.O-O. Now, many ways are decent for Black, such
as 5...dxc4. But I, again, suggest the ambitious 5...e4!} e4 $1 6. Ne1 dxc4 7.
Qa4 Bd6 8. Qxc4 O-O $1 $146 {We don't care! Please note how nicely the e4-pawn
is restraining the White d2-pawn and the e1-knight. Now, White cannot easily
take it as after} 9. Bxe4 (9. Nc3 Nc5 {Now if White takes the pawn, the same
scenario arises where we get a terrific compensation. If he doesn't, how to
develop the queenside?} 10. d3 (10. Nxe4 Ncxe4 11. Bxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Re8 {
Again, we are hitting the e2-pawn.} 13. Qf3 Qe7 {Again, the e2-pawn is our
goal!} 14. e3 c5 $1 {White does not get to develop easily. Let's say, after}
15. d4 Be6 $1 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Nd3 Rad8 $5 18. Nxc5 Qxc5 $36 {White, despite
his extra pawn, is not having a good time because all the Black pieces are
developed a lot better and because all the light squares in his camp are so
weak! Ideas like ...Qc2, ...Rd3, ...Bd5, and so forth provide us with a
fantastic compensation, Black is just better.}) 10... exd3 11. Nxd3 Be6 12. Qd4
Nxd3 13. Qxd3 c6 {Black definitely enjoys a very nice position. Such positions
normally arise from some 1.c4 e5 2.g3 type of English opening, but White
usually has a few extra tempi there. Here, instead, we have all the time in
the world for moves like ...Be7, ...Qa5, ...Rfd8, reaching a very active
position.}) 9... Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Re8 {The e2-pawn is under attack!} 11. Qf3 $8
Ne5 12. Qb3 c5 $1 {We are happy to be a pawn down as long as White cannot
develop. Our ideas will include ...Bh3, or possibly ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7. The
knight will come to d4 via c6. It is truly important to also mention that ...
c5-c4! is a big positional threat. All in all, Black's compensation for the
sacrificed pawn is more than overwhelming!} 13. d3 Bh3 14. Ng2 Nc6 {Black is
again attacking the e2-pawn. We should not be in any hurry to regain the
sacrificed material, as all of our pieces enjoy fantastic positions. For
instance, after} 15. Nc3 Qd7 16. Be3 b6 {We just plan to follow up with moves
like ...Rad8, ...Be5, ...Nd4, and so on. White does not have a single active
move, his position is clearly unattractive.} 17. Rfd1 Be5 18. Qd5 Qc7 $17 {
Black's positional pressure is extremely strong.})) (4. d4 $6 {This was played
in one game only, and for a good reason. After the ambitious} e4 $1 5. Nfd2
$146 (5. Ne5 {And here Black missed a powerful idea} Nb6 $1 $146 {The point is
that now ...f7-f6! is a threat, trapping that e5-knight! White is already in
dire straits.}) 5... f5 6. c4 c6 7. Nc3 Nb6 $15 {Black is just clearly better
as White has some terrible version of the French or Pirc with colours reversed.
Our extra space matters a lot, so does the d5-square after} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 $15 {
I think we can stop here, as after the simple moves like ...Ngf6, ...Be7/d6, ..
.O-O, etc White's opening is clearly proving a failure.}) (4. c4 {At this
point, something like 4...dxc4 is likely to transpose to the analysis we have
later in the chapter, but I think it's a lot more ambitious to react a bit
differently.} e4 $1 5. Ng1 (5. Nd4 $6 {Is not good as after} dxc4 {White
cannot get his pawn back easily, as the d4-knight is unprotected.} 6. Bxe4 $4
Nc5 {[%csl Rd4,Re4] And White is losing a piece.}) 5... dxc4 $1 6. Bxe4 Ngf6 {
Black has given up the center, but he will win tons of time by forcing the
White pieces back with tempi.} 7. Bg2 Ne5 8. Nf3 {How will White castle
otherwise? Nothing terrible has happened to White thus far, but I think it's
clear that to play Nf3-g1-f3 in the opening just to get this knight traded and
to make moves like Bg2-e4-g2-f3 is not a brilliant idea.} Nxf3+ 9. Bxf3 c6 $15
{Black will continue with ...Bc5, ...Be6, ....O-O, etc. It is worth noting
that his c4-pawn is preventing White from moving the d-pawn and thus from
developing his pieces!}) 4... Ngf6 5. O-O {At this point, there are many ways
to develop. Our bishop can go to d6, e7 or c5. It can even stay on its initial
square for a while, if Black chooses to go 5...c6. I prefer the active 5...Bc5!
} Bc5 {One of the reasons why this is not a very common square for the bishop
in the actual Pirc is because White has a typical combination 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7.
d4. When we are White, fighting the Pirc, we don't want such a simplification
to take place. So, the bishop never goes to c5 (or c4, if we are White).
However, as I had stated, we are not as ambitious with Black. If White wants
to simplify to only equalize after the opening, he is welcome to do so! Now,
again, there is a plethora of ways White can continue. I, personally, suggest
that we look at this in the following way: 1) White can either play for e2-e4;
2) Or for c2-c4; 3) Or not decide for either of those two, instead of making
such moves as c2-c3, Re1, Qc2 etc, playing the waiting game; 4) Or he can bail
out with this 6.Nxe5. This is not a forcing position by any means, so I
recommend that you don't try to memorize every single line. Instead, focus on
the typical plans!} (5... Bd6 {If you are looking for a more aggressive way to
play, feel free to look at this move!}) 6. Nbd2 $6 {The most popular move. But,
it was mostly played by players below 2000, with only one game featuring a
2320-rated player. There's a good reason: Black has a very convincing response!
} (6. Nxe5 {This leads to a position not typical of Pirc at all. But, it's a
very safe one for us.} Nxe5 7. d4 Bd6 8. dxe5 Bxe5 {Interestingly, we have
transposed to a position more typically reached via a move order like 1.g3 d5
2.Bg2 e5 or something. There are more games than you'd initially see if you
look via the move order 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Nd7 3.Bg2 e5, but it doesn't matter, as
the evaluation holds true: we have no problems whatsoever.} 9. c4 (9. c3 {
Is another popular move, but I think White should be trying to challenge our
key asset, the d5-pawn. Or else we just finish the development extremely
easily.} O-O 10. Nd2 c6 11. e4 Re8 12. exd5 Nxd5 $11 {Black just has the
slightly better-developed pieces in an otherwise symmetrical position. What
else is there to analyze? Our goal is not to prove Black's advantage after
move 1, so let's be practical and stop here. I would be kind enough to
evaluate this as equality, even though it's rather between equality and
Black's tiny edge.}) 9... c6 (9... dxc4 $6 10. Qc2 $1 {Can actually lead to a
slight White's pressure as his bishop on g2 is especially irritating. This
should better be avoided.}) 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. e4 {This is how two games went -
Black won both, by the way!} Nb4 {At this point, we reach the crossroads.
White can either trade the queens, or try to keep them on the board.} 12. Qxd8+
(12. Qb3 $2 {This is just a big mistake, as now the queen will get kicked
around.} a5 13. Rd1 Qe7 14. Nc3 Be6 $17 {White just kept wasting time to later
lose in a rather unattractive way. His opening was not a success by any means.
0-1 (74) Karasev,V (2405)-Krueger,E (2140) Bad Zwischenahn 2003}) 12... Kxd8
13. Nd2 (13. Nc3 $2 {Is a serious positional mistake as the knight is
misplaced. It has no bright future at all because of the c6-pawn.} Be6 $15 {
[%cal Gd8c7,Ga8d8]}) 13... Nc2 14. Rb1 Be6 15. b3 Ke7 $11 {I think we can stop
here, claiming Black is doing just great. But, I have attached the entire game
- it was a correspondence one, so we can definitely learn quite a lot!} 16. Nc4
Bc3 17. e5 Rhd8 18. Be4 Nb4 19. Bg5+ f6 20. exf6+ gxf6 21. Be3 f5 22. Bf3 Nxa2
23. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 a5 25. Nb6 Rg8 26. Bc5+ Kf6 {0-1 (26) Palacios,E (2005)
-Ronquillo Tamarit,W (2200) ICCF email 2015}) (6. c3 {White is not defining
his plans yet. We will simply castle to see what he's been up to.} O-O {
We know that we are happy to react to d3-d4 with ...Bd6, reaching the same
positions as after 6.Nxe5. If White just plays it calmly with 7.Qc2, we'll
continue making useful moves - say, after} 7. Qc2 Re8 {White already has to be
careful as ...e5-e4! might hit him quite hard!} 8. e4 dxe4 9. dxe4 a5 $15 {
We transpose to the similar positions as after the immediate ...e2-e4, but
with the queen on c2. I think, again, the same ideas and evaluations hold true:
Black is at least very comfortable, possibly just better.}) (6. e4 $146 {
This has never been played, as White is clearly not ready for this move. Still,
let's see how we react.} dxe4 7. dxe4 O-O 8. Qe2 a5 $1 {I really like this
positional move. There are several ideas behind it. First of all, we are
preventing any potential c2-c3 and b2-b4-related ideas. Secondly, we are
possibly preparing stuff like ...b7-b6 or even ...b7-b5! followed by ...Ba6.
Now the game is not forcing by any means, but it's fair enough to say that
White is likely to make moves like Nbd2, c2-c3, maybe Nf3-h4-f5. We will, on
the other hand, strive to play ...Qe7, ...c7-c6, ... possibly ...Rd8 or ...Re8.
Maybe the knight will go to e6 via c5 or via f8.} 9. Rd1 (9. c3 Qe7 10. Nbd2 b6
$1 {The bishop is coming to a6 and White just ends up worse.} 11. Rd1 Ba6 12.
Qe1 $4 Ng4 $19 {Suddenly this is over.}) 9... Qe7 10. Nc3 c6 {Taking the d5
and b5-squares under control.} 11. Bh3 Re8 12. Bg5 Nf8 {The knight is coming
to e6, while also allowing for the bishop trade, which accelerates our
development.} 13. Bxc8 Raxc8 14. a4 {It makes sense for White to stop any
potential ...b7-b5 ideas.} Ne6 $11 {White can take or retreat, but anyway, we
have no concerns whatsoever here! The plan is very simple - we just want to
use the open d-file and the d4-square, while the knight on c3 is really
misplaced.}) (6. c4 {This is another reasonable attempt. Again, I like the
idea of releasing the tension immediately} dxc4 7. dxc4 O-O 8. Nc3 {This is
how most games went, and here I am suggesting a slightly unexpected move. I
think you would agree that 8...c6 is the most natural continuation, taking the
d5 and b5-squares under control. But, I like the new idea} Re8 $1 $146 {
The reason is that we can always play ...c7-c6 later, but we are now preparing
the f8-square for the bishop in the event of Na4. Now, it is not really clear
how White should continue. The most natural way seems to be} (8... c6 9. Na4 $1
(9. b3 Qe7 10. Bb2 {0-1 (28) Martinez Balaguer,J (1938) -Losada Carrera,F 
(2199) Barbera del Valles 2006}) 9... Be7 10. Qc2 $36 {Now White might try
a2-a3, b2-b4, c4-c5, getting some play on the queenside. This is definitely
playable, but should rather be avoided.}) 9. b3 {But then we immediately
answer with} c6 {Na4 is not a problem anymore, so we happily make this move.}
10. Bb2 Qe7 11. Na4 (11. Qc2 Nf8 12. Rad1 e4 $1 $146 {Again, . ..e4-e3 is a
powerful idea. But also, ...h7-h5-h4! could be a nice plan, taking advantage
of the missing knight on f3.} (12... Bg4 {Was played in the game, but I am not
sure I like it so much. 0-1 (28) Martinez Balaguer,J (1938) -Losada Carrera,F 
(2199) Barbera del Valles 2006}) 13. Nd4 h5 $1 {Black can continue with ...
e4-e3, or ...h4-h3, or even activate the knight on f8 by means of ...Ng6 or ...
N8h7-g5! We are definitely doing great here.}) 11... Ba3 $1 12. Bxa3 Qxa3 13.
Qc1 Qe7 {We want to go ...Nc5 and trade the knights. Later, ...a5-a4-a3 could
be a nice plan, trying to get some play on the queenside.}) (6. Nc3 {This
prepares e2-e4. We will react similarly as to the immediate e2-e4.} c6 7. e4
dxe4 8. dxe4 (8. Nxe4 {It is also possible to trade the knights, but the
evaluation is not changing much, we are doing great anyway.} Nxe4 9. dxe4 O-O {
Now the natural plan is Qe2, Rd1, Be3 etc.} 10. Qe2 {I don't think it's worth
memorizing any specific plans here. But, we need to understand the setups and
plans. The queen will go to e7 or c7, we will place the rook on e8, the knight
will come to f6. It is worth mentioning that ...a7-a5 is a useful move, both
intending to prevent c2-c3 and b2-b4 as well as to meet b2-b3 with ...a5-a4!,
getting counterplay over the a-file!} Qe7 $132 {[%cal Ra7a5,Ra5a4,Rb7b6,Rc8a6,
Gd7f6,Gf8e8,Rf8d8]}) 8... O-O 9. Qe2 Re8 {Again, I like this move, which
protects the e5-pawn and makes room on f8 either for our knight, which will go
to f8-e6-d4, or for the bishop in the event of any Na4 type of stuff.} 10. Nh4
{This is what Morozevich went for against Ivanchuk. However, I think Black is
already somewhat better, and the most aggressive way to try to prove it would
have been} b5 $1 11. Nf5 {And here comes a very unexpected, yet a very strong
move. We would like to kick the f5-knight away, but ...g7-g6 allows for Nh6+.
So, we will now play} h5 $3 $146 {The idea is that after ...g7-g6 the knight
wouldn't want to go to h6 anymore as it will end up trapped there! Black is
just better as he intends to play ...g7-g6, ...Bf8, ...Nc5, ...a7-a5, maybe ...
b5-b4 and ...Ba6.}) 6... e4 $1 (6... O-O {Is also possible, but less ambitious.
Why not take advantage of White's last move?}) 7. dxe4 (7. Nh4 $2 e3 8. fxe3
Ng4 $17 {As usual, whenever this typical idea is blundered in the Pirc type of
positions, the side who blunders it (usually Black, or now White as we are
looking at it with colours reversed), ends up in tons of trouble.}) 7... dxe4
8. Nh4 e3 9. fxe3 {Now Black has many good continuations. The engine believes
the strongest move is short castling, just not caring about the pawns. But in
order to keep this simple and clear, I would settle for the most convincing
and self-explanatory move.} Bxe3+ {We immediately get the pawn back.} 10. Kh1
O-O 11. Nf5 Ng4 $15 {It is possible to go deeper in the lines, but it is clear
that Black is at least not worse. Or, to be more precise, White is the one
fighting hard for his life.} *

