{[%evp 0,178,30,30,18,-9,25,29,44,50,52,37,28,26,51,27,-5,-4,14,14,-1,2,2,-6,
-14,-59,37,75,75,75,87,69,57,74,45,40,40,38,37,35,38,1,5,5,13,13,0,5,5,0,0,40,
26,46,26,0,0,0,33,0,39,26,42,0,0,-27,-69,-61,-73,-87,-98,-98,-100,-100,-100,
-100,-100,-100,-100,-100,-100,-100,-100,-100,-100,-100,-100,-100,50,0,0,-44,
-56,-117,-126,-134,-133,-129,-135,-137,-136,-141,-134,-168,-170,-181,-153,-156,
-134,-201,-218,-216,-233,-232,-214,-220,-213,-209,-207,-238,-207,-220,-214,
-228,-238,-238,-223,-231,-231,-245,-250,-245,-245,-245,-245,-245,-245,-245,
-223,-230,-243,-242,-247,-251,-241,-246,-235,-245,-232,-246,-250,-251,-250,
-269,-269,-275,-278,-270,-281,-278,-278,-351,-416,-435,-233,-245,-159,-158,
-159,-225,-228,-246,-267,-289,-302,-399,-489,-628,-308,-1097,-1310]} 1. Nf3 d5
2. g3 Nd7 3. d4 $1 {Okay, this is the real deal. White prevents ...e7-e5 and
clearly states he is not interested in playing some Pirc in the first hand or
something. Now the question is how we are going to explain and justify the
position of the knight on d7.} Nb6 $5 {This is the key fresh diea that was
discovered just recently and that made me interested in creating this
repertoire with 2...Nd7 at its core. Black firmly takes the c4-square under
control and prepares the convenient development with ...Bf5 and ...e7-e6. This
way, he would have no bad pieces, his bishop won't be locked in. At the same
time, White won't be able to play c2-c4 easily.} 4. Bg2 (4. Nbd2 {White can go
for this move immediately, but it does not make much sense if it's followed
with Bg2, as White could have easily started with Bg2, not committing his
knight to this square early. But, there is one additional idea we need to look
at.} Bf5 5. Nh4 $5 {White immediately goes after our bishop. At this point, I
suggest that we follow Bluebaum steps with} e6 $1 6. Nxf5 exf5 7. Bg2 c6 $1 {
I like this move better. After castling, we will transpose back to something
very similar to Bluebaum's game, but we would have cut out the possibility of
c2-c4.} (7... Nf6 $6 8. e3 (8. c4 $1 {Would have been unpleasant as taking
isn't possible because of the hanging b7-pawn.}) 8... c6 $11 {Black managed to
equalize, here White's already not fighting for anything. 0-1 (30) Blohberger,
F (2434)-Bluebaum,M (2644) Moscow 2019}) 8. O-O Nf6 {Black has an extremely
solid position. Unfortunately, his results in the two games that reached this
position haven't been great, but that is only caused by a significant
difference in players' strength.} 9. c3 h5 $5 $146 {Would have been an
interesting idea. Possibly, we are just grabbing space, but maybe we are also
intending ...h5-h4! This forces the White knight to go to f3.} (9... g6 10. f3
Bg7 11. e4 fxe4 12. fxe4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 O-O {Black still has a
very solid position here! But, I don't really see a good reason why we needed
to allow for this pawn break. Now it's still equal as we would place our
knight on d5, and if White is to ever chase it with c3-c4, it would massively
weaken the d4-pawn. Also, importantly, the White kingside has been seriously
weakened, just as the e3-square. After ...Qd7, ....Rae8 and ...Nd5 the
e3-square is clearly something to watch out for! Also, as the f-pawn just
disappeared, ideas with ...h5-h4! look very nasty. Black is clearly doing fine.
} 15. Bg2 Qd7 16. Bf4 Rfe8 17. Qf3 Nd5 18. Bd2 f5 (18... h5 $1 $11 {As I said,
it would have been very natural to push the h-pawn instead.}) 19. Rae1 Nf6 20.
Qd3 Qf7 {This position is still equal, but later Black was too keen on trading,
which made him lose all the dynamic chances and eventually White's bishop pair
did tell. 1-0 (51) Burmakin,V (2514)-Le Goff,R (2281) Rochefort 2020}) 10. Nf3
Be7 {Now, we can just follow with ...O-O, ...Re8, ...Ne4, etc. White mustn't
have any pawn breaks at all, unlike in the game, and his bishop pair does not
really matter. Especially the bishop on g2, look at it! What's it doing out
there?}) 4... Bf5 5. O-O e6 {We now reach a very interesting and fresh
position, which has been reached in 11 games only, 10 of which have been
played in late 2019 and in 2020! The position clearly isn't too forcing or
anything, so we don't need to memorize the lines by heart. But, it's worth
looking at the possible scenarios of how the game can develop.} 6. b3 {White's
idea is to prepare c2-c4. As we know, we are not too afraid of that advance,
anyway! Now many ways of continuing are possible, but since White had just
spent a tempo, I suggest taking our time to safeguard the f5-bishop's life.} (
6. Nh4 {At this point, we have two solid choices.} Bg4 $1 7. h3 Bh5 8. Nd2 Be7
9. Nhf3 Nf6 $11 {White didn't even manage to get the bishop pair, so his
previous play was pointless. It's worth seeing how Black went on to continue,
though, as his play was rather instructive.} 10. b3 O-O 11. Bb2 a5 $1 {A
typical idea - we are creating tension on the queenside.} 12. c4 c6 13. Rc1 a4
$1 14. Qc2 axb3 15. axb3 Bg6 16. Qd1 Ra2 $36 {Black already clearly started
taking over. 0-1 (27) Schein,L (1584)-Hechl,G (2333) Playchess. com INT 2020})
(6. Ne5 {This move has been played twice, but it was seen in arguably the most
important game ever played in this line!} c6 7. c4 $5 {Karjakin is making a
very natural move, but in fact, this is already begging for the massive
complications!} (7. Nd2 {Would have been a normal solid way of continuing, but
after} Nf6 8. Re1 Bd6 $11 {It's clear that Black has no problems in this
typical position. For example, one plan for White can be to push e2-e4, but it
does not lead anywhere.} 9. Nd3 O-O 10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Qf6 13.
Bxf5 Qxf5 $11 {We will continue with ...Rd8, ...Nd7, ... c6-c5 with a
completely equal position. Such situations can only be dangerous for Black
when White either has a lot of pieces on the board, as we have less space, or
when he can quickly generate a lot of activity on the kingside. It's clear
that neither of the two is the case here, so we are doing just fine.}) 7... f6
$5 {Alekseenko goes for it!} (7... Nf6 {Would have been a completely normal,
solid choice, where Black is by no means worse. For example, after} 8. Nd2 Be7
9. Qb3 O-O 10. c5 Nbd7 $11 {Taking the b7-pawn is clearly not good because of .
..Nxe5 and ...Nd7, ruining White's structure, while otherwise Black is by no
means challenged.}) 8. cxd5 fxe5 9. dxc6 e4 10. cxb7 Rb8 $13 {Imagine, how
interesting and fascinating it would be to explore such a position! White
definitely has some very interesting compensation, but a piece is a piece, and
soon it turned out White had the more difficult time handling this.} 11. Nc3
Nf6 12. Bg5 Be7 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nxe4 {Both sides are just developing and
making the very natural and forcing moves, let us see what happened shortly.}
Bxe4 15. Bxe4 Qxd4 16. Qc2 Qc4 17. Qxc4 Nxc4 18. Rfd1 Nxb2 19. Bc6+ Kf8 $13 {
It's definitely still roughly balanced, but I can rather imagine Black
neutralizing White's activity as opposed to White getting anywhere here. Soon
Karjakin went on to make a few inaccuracies and lose.} 20. Rd7 $6 {The most
natural move proves wrong!} Nd3 $1 21. Rd1 Nc5 $1 22. R7d2 Kf7 $15 {Black
finally forced the opponent to retreat and later went on to win in an
excellent style. 0-1 (89) Karjakin,S (2760)-Alekseenko,K (2674) Douglas 2019})
(6. Nbd2 Be7 $1 $146 {At this point, I find it rather important to present
this early novelty. We are stopping Nh4 and are preparing to develop with ...
Nf6, possibly ...h7-h6. White has two possible plans to try and execute -
c2-c4 or e2-e4.} (6... Nf6 {Has been played by a GM, but I don't see any point
in allowing the additional option of Nh4, at least so early. We might let
White play this later, but first, let's see what he does now. While what
arises is a very solid position for Black, why would we give White an extra
option without getting anything in return?}) 7. c4 (7. Re1 Nf6 8. Nh4 {Now, we
still did allow for Nh4, but White had also made the move Re1, which isn't
necessarily the most useful one. I think we have a few very decent
continuations.} O-O 9. Nxf5 exf5 $11 {This structure is solid, but now it's
even more justified as the rook is feeling rather dumb on e1. White is clearly
never ever getting e2-e4 in! This position is all about the structure, and we
are discussing this typical structure in many other places throughout this
chapter, so let's cut the analysis short here and say Black is clearly fine.
His following moves will be ...Re8, ...c6, ...Bd6, ...Ne4, and so on.}) 7... c6
8. Qb3 $5 {This is another interesting idea, which is making us react
immediately as the b7-pawn might hang after c4-c5.} Qc7 $5 $11 {If the knight
was on c3, White would have been undoubtedly better. At the moment, though,
his knight is extremely misplaced and it really difficult to understand how he
should proceed. Taking on d5 makes very little sense, to push e2-e4 is
impossible, c4-c5 does not yield anything, either. Most likely White will just
make a few waiting moves, try to meet ...Nf6 with Nh4, get the bishop pair and
play this calm, solid position where neither side is experiencing any issues.}
(8... Nf6 $4 {Now the pawn sacrifice does not make any sense, unlike the case
when the White knight is on e5, as we cannot create counterplay by taking that
knight and garbaging the White structure.} 9. c5 Nbd7 10. Qxb7 $18 {This is
just lost.})) 6... h6 $5 {I consider saving the bishop with ...h7-h6 a luxury,
but that's the luxury White just offered us to have, why not enjoy it?} (6...
c6 7. c4 Nf6 8. Nh4 $11 {Is also completely possible, and is very much in the
spirit of the rest of the chapter!}) 7. c4 c6 (7... dxc4 $2 {Would open the
long diagonal and result in terrible consequences. For instance, after} 8. bxc4
Nxc4 $4 9. Qa4+ $18 {Black is losing a piece, while if he didn't take, it's
not possible to justify the move ...dxc4.}) 8. Nc3 Nf6 9. Ne5 Nbd7 10. Nd3 Be7
11. f3 {The game continued in this natural way, when White was preparing to
push e2-e4. That was the point when Black had to be somewhat precise and
choose the future course of action.} O-O $1 (11... c5 $6 {To undermine the
center was clearly somewhat premature as Black wasn't developed enough.} 12. e4
$1 dxe4 (12... cxd4 $1 {Would have still led to an unclear situation, which
shows Black's resources are rather ample.} 13. exf5 dxc3 14. fxe6 fxe6 $13 {
[%csl Rf3,Rg2][%cal Ge8g8,Gh8f8,Ge6e5] It's truly difficult to analyze such
fresh positions much deeper, but Black is definitely fine here.}) 13. fxe4 Bg4
14. Ne2 Nh7 15. h3 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 cxd4 17. e5 $1 {1-0 (27) Hou,Y (2664)
-Fedoseev,V (2677) Jinan 2019}) 12. e4 Bh7 $1 {As it's easy to see, the White
center is under a substantial amount of pressure. Our plan might involve ...
Qa5 and ...Ba3, which is especially effective if the White bishop goes to b2.
It's also possible to continue with ...Qa5, ...Rd8 etc, applying even more
pressure on the center. Now it looks like White can seize even more space, but
that does not lead to an easy life for him.} 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. e5 Ne8 15. f4
Nc7 $1 {Black will get plenty of counterplay coon with ...Nb8-c6-b4, ...Rc8,
possibly ...Nb5-c3. At the same time, White cannot really achieve anything on
the kingside as his pieces are misplaced for the kingside action - just look
at his knights! Also, Black can always rely on the typical French-themed ...
f7-f5!, which would stop White's kingside play. It's interesting that even the
engine, which is usually so happy about the space advantage, thinks the
position is just even.} *

