{[%evp 0,135,19,29,23,-8,17,3,10,17,21,-9,-22,-5,27,3,12,12,12,23,40,49,43,42,
55,39,39,44,59,51,40,38,42,42,82,-1,60,74,70,70,90,70,70,68,69,19,28,34,27,17,
64,48,54,31,71,68,59,81,126,61,75,95,130,113,115,104,114,119,106,103,129,74,88,
77,56,48,31,41,38,-56,-63,-67,-68,-130,-101,-179,-172,-176,-115,-121,-126,-130,
-54,-130,-62,-50,-50,-31,-11,-21,-11,-6,-6,-5,0,-20,0,-23,-18,-36,-24,-30,-21,
-27,-30,-30,-11,-15,0,11,11,0,17,16,16,-548,17,17,17,17,17,17,17,16,19,16,16,
15]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 Bg4 $5 {After a long hesitation, I've decided to
recommend this move. The hesitations weren't related to the quality of the
move - it's perfectly good and sound. The thing is that Black has multiple
interesting setups against 2.b3, but finally I thought this was the most
straightforward path. What's the idea and philosophy behind 2...Bg4? In fact,
we are playing some kind of a Trompowsky reversed. But, the pawn on b3 harms
exactly White in many lines. For example, in many Trompowsky lines Black goes .
..c7-c5 and ...Qb6 or ...Qa5. So, logically, with colours reversed, we'd need
to watch out for stuff like Qb3 or Qa4. But, the pawn on b3 makes this idea
impossible to execute! Or, here's another benefit. In Trompowsky, after 1.d4
Nf6 2.Bg5 d5, this structure is considered rather solid for Black, but if he
has a move ...b7-b6 in, even for free, it's often making his structure loose.
There are several other benefits - I can't name them all here as that'd take a
few pages, but I hope this already makes perfect sense. Now, we will divide
the material after 2.b3 Bg4 into three parts - where White ignores the ...Bxf3
idea with 3.Bb2, where he plays 3.e3 or where he aggressively jumps out and
attacks us with 3.Ne5.} (2... c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Bb2 {Actually, while this setup
is definitely decent, I think that White does have reasons to fight for an
edge.}) 3. Bb2 {This position mostly arises via 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 Bg4 3.Nf3, so
you will also be almost ready to meet 1.b3 :)} Bxf3 {We immediately take,
spoiling White's structure. Now, two way of recapturing are possible, but 4.
exf3 is preferred in the vast majority of cases.} 4. exf3 (4. gxf3 {This is
also a possibility, but I am not a huge fan of this idea as Black will easily
extinguish all the possible activity down the g-file White might count on with
...g7-g6, and the White king might have the harder time finding a good shelter
now.} e6 5. e3 Nf6 6. f4 {Typically most games continue in this way, where we
choose the setup very typical and reminiscent of one we use against 4.exf3.
Again, the pawn goes to g6 and the bishop goes to g7, challenging White's
activity down the long dark diagonal and preparing to deprive White of his
bishop pair.} g6 7. c4 Bg7 8. d3 O-O 9. Nd2 {Those few games that reached this
position went this way, and here, I believe, we can again make White an offer
he will be hardly able to turn down.} Nh5 $5 {We would love the trade, while
if White declines, he will encounter severe dynamic problems.} 10. d4 $2 (10.
Bxg7 Nxg7 11. d4 c6 12. Bg2 Nd7 $11 {We reach another very solid position,
similar to the ones we get in the main line. We might just continue with ...
a7-a5-a4, getting some play on the queenside while simultaneously taming the
g2-bishop. It's equal, but a little more fun for Black.}) 10... c5 $1 {[%csl
Rb2,Rc4,Rd4][%cal Gg7b2]} 11. Nf3 Nc6 $17 {Black is pressuring the center like
crazy and White always needs to watch out for the weak f4-pawn, as the knight
on h5 is doing a fantastic job. Also, the ...Qa5+ might prove very disruptive
and dangerous! White's already nearly lost.}) 4... e6 {It makes sense to make
this calm move first, not defining the intentions yet. Generally, we'd hope to
play ...Nf6, ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7. It's important to understand we would
welcome almost any situation where the position would close down quite a bit,
as the opponent has two bishops. But, we can boast of a better structure, so
the long-term goal would involve keeping the position closed and trading one
of his bishops, if possible. We'll likely succeed if we play ... g7-g6 and ...
Bg7 and simply move our knight from f6 - this offer will be hard to turn down.}
(4... h5 $5 {We will see this idea later in the text, but to be honest, I am
quite tempted to play this even now! This could be something you might want to
investigate additionally yourself. In a nutshell, we want to provoke h2-h4
which would make White's structure more rigid and inflexible.} 5. Be2 h4 6. O-O
) 5. g3 (5. f4 {White can immediatly advance his f-pawn as well, but we will
react in a similar manner.} Nf6 (5... h5 $5 {Is another interesting
possibility, hinting that we'd want to meet g2-g3 with ...h5-h4 or advance the
h-pawn anyway. h2-h4, on the other hand, deprives White of flexibility and
makes his pawns fixed on the dark squares which is exactly what we want.}) 6.
g3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O {White has tried several setups here, but we are
discussing similar positions in the main line, so let's cut our analysis short
here. It's important to realize it's not about memorization at this point, but
much rather about plans/ideas/favorable trades.}) 5... h5 $146 {Surprisingly,
that's a novelty as soon as on 5th move! The idea is very logical, though, and
can be encountered in many other openings. You play g2-g3 or ...g7-g6 - better
be ready for the Harry's advance!} 6. h4 {This is the more solid and sound
option, stopping all the potential shenanigans on the kingside Black could try
to come up with.} (6. Bg2 h4 $1 {In my opinion, this is a little too risky for
White, especially because our knight isn't on f6 yet. In the event of castling,
we can continue with ...Qg5-h6 followed by ...hxg3, creating some rather
straightforward threats on the kingside!} 7. O-O Qg5 (7... hxg3 8. hxg3 Nc6 {
Also makes perfect sense, not defining the position of our queen yet. We can
easily castle long in such positions, too!} 9. f4 Nh6 $5 {The knight belongs
to f5 now! It's not possible to analyse things too deeply here as we have NO
games in the database after some 6-7 moves, which is fantastic news - the
position presents plenty of room for creativity. Just keep in mind you'd want
to go ...Nf5, ...Qd7, ...0-0-0 and let the fun begin!}) 8. f4 Qh6 9. Re1 $8 {
The engine suggests White is fine, but I am not sure anyone would want to go
here as White!}) 6... Nf6 7. Bg2 g6 {Now we stick to our positional business
again. Remember to develop the bishop to g7 with the idea to rival the White
one on the long diagonal and to trade them in the future! The Black pawns are
all set on the light squares which makes his bishop amazing and builds a nice
wall against the g2-bishop.} 8. f4 Bg7 9. O-O O-O {At this point, White can
try several things. He can choose to play d2-d4, or to develop more flexibly
with d2-d3, keeping his options open.} 10. d4 (10. d3 Ng4 $5 {Many other
options were available, but like I said, I want to deprive White of one of his
aces - the bishop pair. Declining the offer with something like c2-c3 is just
silly because the b2-bishop will look really dumb, while the g4-knight will be
having a lovely time on that outpost.} 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Nd2 {Now we can
either choose the waiting strategy like in the main line by playing this .. .
Nc6-e7 plan, meeting c2-c4 with ...c7-c6 and stuff. Or, we can choose to push .
..c7-c5 ourselves, which after c2-c4 will result in a more open position where
both sides will have more opportunities to fight for a win - in either case,
we have nothing to worry about!} Nc6 $13 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5,Ge6,Rg2][%cal Gc6e7,
Rc7c6]} (12... c5 $132 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gb8c6,Rd8e7,Gd8d7,Ga8d8,Gf8e8]})) 10... Nc6
$1 {Another very cool idea. Where's the knight going? You're gonna see shortly!
} 11. Nd2 Ne7 $1 12. Nf3 Nf5 $1 $13 {The knight is placed extremely solidly on
f5, but if needed, it can come to d6 and to e4, or to d6 and just stay there,
controlling the c4 and e4-squares. Later, we can prepare . ..a7-a5-a4,
initiating some play on the queenside. Both of the White bishops must be
rather passive and useless. We won't even open up the game too much, and we'll
meet c2-c4 with ...c7-c6, leaving White wondering how to make use of his
bishops. One interesting plan could involve moving the f8-rook somewhere and
playing ...Bf8, possibly supporting the ...a7-a5-a4 plan. Black is doing just
great here.} *

