{[%evp 0,110,42,31,23,-7,-1,-11,2,-32,-24,-12,-8,2,13,-8,1,4,12,6,4,10,24,7,44,
19,18,18,20,1,12,12,14,12,23,16,25,11,35,24,24,29,32,35,64,76,91,95,95,74,75,
92,88,88,88,92,83,80,80,80,106,108,102,102,99,99,100,106,108,110,104,92,101,87,
96,87,100,88,91,67,75,74,75,68,71,79,78,72,72,74,84,68,83,83,78,79,115,94,81,
79,47,14,13,8,6,8,8,7,8,3,0,0,0]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 Bg4 $5 {After a long
hesitation, I've decided to recommend this move. The hesitations weren't
related to the quality of the move - it's perfectly good and sound. The thing
is that Black has multiple interesting setups against 2.b3, but finally I
thought this was the most straightforward path. What's the idea and philosophy
behind 2...Bg4? In fact, we are playing some kind of a Trompowsky reversed.
But, the pawn on b3 harms exactly White in many lines. For example, in many
Trompowsky lines Black goes ...c7-c5 and ...Qb6 or ...Qa5. So, logically, with
colours reversed, we'd need to watch out for stuff like Qb3 or Qa4. But, the
pawn on b3 makes this idea impossible to execute! Or, here's another benefit.
In Trompowsky, after 1.d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 d5, this structure is considered rather
solid for Black, but if he has a move ...b7-b6 in, even for free, it's often
making his structure loose. There are several other benefits - I can't name
them all here as that'd take a few pages, but I hope this already makes
perfect sense. Now, we will divide the material after 2.b3 Bg4 into three
parts - where White ignores the ...Bxf3 idea with 3.Bb2, where he plays 3.e3
or where he aggressively jumps out and attacks us with 3.Ne5.} (2... c5 3. e3
Nf6 4. Bb2 {Actually, while this setup is definitely decent, I think that
White does have reasons to fight for an edge.}) 3. e3 {A very sensible move
and the second most popular one: White wants to get a calm get where we cannot
manage to spoil their pawns. Yet, I believe, to have a bishop on g4 is very
convenient as now we can easily build this wall with ...c7-c6, ...e7-e6, etc,
without being afraid to bury our bishop inside.} e6 {So far we keep developing.
} 4. Bb2 Nd7 5. Be2 (5. h3 {Can be played right now, but is likely to
transpose to 5.Be2 followed to 6.h3. The only independent attempt is to play
g2-g4 immediately.} Bh5 6. g4 Bg6 7. h4 {This is the only continuation that
tries to make sense of this g2-g4 play. But, I fail to see how this achieves
anything after either ...h7-h6 or the more ambitious} h5 $1 8. g5 Ne7 {We
reach some weird setup which is quite similar to the one Black uses in the
Advance Caro-Kann. The plan can be to continue with ...Nf5, keeping the
h4-pawn under attack, or with ...c7-c5 and ...Nc6, followed even my ...e6-e5!
This is another brand-new position which is very interesting and complicated,
but I feel White took more obligations and responsibilities on himself with
this h2-h4 and g2-g2-g4.}) 5... Ngf6 6. O-O {White can also play in a similar
manner without h2-h3. Again, there's no need to deviate from a very similar
way of development.} (6. h3 Bh5 7. d3 {This is a fairly tricky move order
where White might choose to go after our bishop with g2-g4 and Nh4. That is
fine, but I'd rather avoid this altogether.} h6 $5 8. Nbd2 Bg6 $5 {Preparing
to meet Nh4 and preventing e3-e4.} 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 O-O 11. Bf1 {White is
preparing e3-e4.} a5 $1 {We immediately grab space on the other side of the
board. Please note that this ...a7-a5 is a highly typical idea in all these
positions, as the b3-pawn is a perfect hook!} 12. e4 Be7 13. e5 {Now, White
can keep the tension with moves like a2-a3, but it's important to understand
that we are not afraid of e4-e5 in these positions as the b2-bishop
immediately gets useless while ours on g6 springs to life.} Ne8 14. d4 c5 {
We immediately tackle the White center. White already needs to react precisely
in order not to end up worse.} 15. c4 $1 Nc7 $1 $132 {We have plenty of
counterplay on the queenside, while the b2-bishop is a terrible piece. I
definitely think it'd be easier to handle this as Black - this looks to me
like a Caro-Kann with 3-4 extra tempi.}) 6... Bd6 7. c4 {This is another setup,
which attempts to keep things more flexible for now. White might play d2-d3 or
d2-d4. Okay, no problem!} c6 8. d4 (8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2 {For sure, we cannot be
possibly experiencing any problems if White handles the opening in such a
sheepless way. Yet, it's important to understand what the plan is.} e5 $1 {
For one, I'd take the center right away.} 10. h3 Bh5 11. Nh4 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Re8
$146 (12... g6 {Was also good, but I am not sure if I want to immediately
weaken the a1-h8 diagonal. 0-1 (42) Kunin,V (2462)-Khenkin,I (2595) Osterburg
2006}) 13. Nf5 Bf8 $132 {We enjoy the beautiful center and can kick the
f5-knight out anytime. I won't exaggerate and say that Black is already better,
but he is at least very comfortable. Another possible plan might involve ...
a7-a5, ...b7-b5, and so on, with some interesting play on the queenside.}) (8.
h3 {Transposes to the variation we discuss after 8.c4} Bh5 9. d3 O-O 10. Nbd2 {
0-1 (42) Kunin,V (2462)-Khenkin,I (2595) Osterburg 2006}) 8... Ne4 $1 (8... O-O
9. Nbd2 {Is also very good for Black, but I am a bit more concerned as it's
not so easy to play ...Ne4 without allowing White to take. Actually, this
position is very decent, and such fantastic players as Carlsen, Karjakin,
Dreev and many others went here as Black. But, I feel that my solution is even
simpler.}) 9. Nbd2 f5 {We immediately build a fantastic Stonewall where the
typically bad c8-bishop is out on g4. Black is doing just great, for example}
10. Ne5 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 O-O 12. Ndf3 a5 13. a3 Qe7 14. Nd3 Rf6 15. Nfe5 Bxe5 16.
dxe5 Rh6 $36 {And Black went on to develop the fairly classic Stonewall-type
initiative. 0-1 (39) Kulikov,A (2395)-Morozevich,A (2590) Moscow 1998} *

