{[%evp 0,67,28,17,16,-9,0,-33,-44,-32,-30,-34,2,-15,19,27,15,-17,-3,-3,-13,-52,
-13,-9,19,5,13,9,25,13,21,11,25,-12,-15,-36,-79,-72,-8,-171,-183,-277,-277,
-296,-58,-263,-189,-213,-41,-215,-117,-107,-109,-101,-119,-129,-98,-97,-101,
-122,-106,-101,-10,-26,0,0,0,-437,29991,29992]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. g3 {
This is a way of playing that can be rather popular with people who want to
avoid the direct conflicts early on and just wish to play a maneuvring game.
It is well known that there's one issue with this approach: namely, Black
hasn't committed to ...c7-c5 yet, which means he can save a tempo on this.} Nc6
4. Bg2 (4. d3 e5 5. Bg2 {Just transposes to 4.Bg2 5.d3}) 4... e5 {At this
point, White faces a choice. He can either play d2-d3, which is considered
undesirable in these structures because it allows for a nasty check on b4, or
castle immediately.} 5. d3 (5. O-O {This is also a possibility. Here, we have
two choices: to simply continue in a positional style with moves like ...Nf6,
meeting a2-a3 with ...a7-a5, etc. But, I like the even more aggressive and
ambitious approach.} e4 $5 {This move was used even back in 1970s a few times,
but as it is seen currently, it is brought to the top-level chess by Wojtaczek.
} 6. Ne1 h5 $1 {This is Radoslaw's idea from 2005 which definitely proved very
reasonable and withstood the test of time rather reliably. Now, White can
either take the pawn immediately, or decline the invitation with d2-d3 - in
fact, this is the most popular White choice.} 7. d3 (7. Bxe4 {It's funny that
Wojtaczek, who invented the whole idea, never faced this principled move. Now,
of course, we will continue with} h4 (7... Bh3 $5 {Is also quite interesting.
Here, funnily, White's only move is} 8. Qb3 $1 {I won't go in too much detail,
check this out yourself as an alternative solution.}) 8. d3 (8. Bg2 hxg3 9.
hxg3 $2 (9. fxg3 Nf6 10. d3 Bh3 $1 {Black's ideas - ...Qd7 and long castling
followed by the attack - are very straightforward. I don't find it too
reasonable to go into too much detail here because we are on a completely
unexplored ground and both sides' play isn't forced, but believe me: when you
see a position like this, where Black is a pawn down, and the engine is
showing Black is already clearly better, it's a very bad sign. Likely, if we
dig deeper, White is nearly lost or is forced to transpose into some endgame
an exchange or a few pawns down or something.}) 9... Qg5 $17 {...Qh5 is about
to come and it's barely possible to do anything about it.}) 8... Bh3 9. Ng2 (9.
Bg2 {Isn't good because of the reasons explained elsewhere in this line.} Qd7
$17 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gg8f6,Rh4g3] The simple development, such as ...0-0-0, ...Nf6,
...hxg3 etc will just kill White.}) 9... Qd7 {Five games have reached this
position. The statistics haven't been too positive for Black, who scored only
1/5. But, in fact, Black's position is much better, and I believe it would be
very instructive to follow one game of an extremely bright and gifted
Ukrainian junior, who was handling this really well but lost due to an
unfortunate blunder.} 10. Bf4 Nf6 11. Bf3 Bd6 (11... hxg3 {Was even stronger,
the point being to meet} 12. Bxg3 {with} Ng4 $1 {Black follows with ...Bd6 and
the pressure on h2 becomes unbearable.}) 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Nd2 g5 $1 {Natural
and strong. The position is still balanced, but I think it's clearly more
enjoyable to be Black.} 14. Qb3 O-O-O 15. c5 $6 {White understandably seeks
counterplay, but this move concedes the d5-square.} Qe7 16. Qa4 Nd5 17. Rfe1
hxg3 18. hxg3 Qe6 $19 {Now it's totally over, as ideas like ...Qh6 and ...Ne5
simply cannot be stopped.} 19. e4 Ndb4 20. e5 Qh6 21. Be4 Bg4 22. f3 Bh3 23.
Nf1 Bxg2 24. Kxg2 Nc2 $6 {The step in the wrong direction.} (24... Qh1+ $1 25.
Kf2 Rh2+ 26. Nxh2 Qxh2+ 27. Kf1 Rh8 $19 {Was an immediate finish as ...Qg3 and
...Rh2/h1 cannot be stopped.}) 25. Kf2 Nxa1 26. Rxa1 a6 27. Re1 Qe6 28. g4 $17
{Black still was clearly better, but unfortunately, later he went on to commit
a terrible blunder and had to resign. I felt really bad as my friend who had
the Black pieces really deserved to win, he handled this position in a very
creative and talented manner! Unfortunately, sometimes blunders prove too
costly. 1-0 (34) Tomici,S (2319)-Galperin,P (2439) Lvov 2019}) 7... e3 $1 {
I find the idea aimed at depriving the White king's shelter of another
defender - the f-pawn - most appealing.} (7... h4 {Is also possible and good
enough.}) 8. fxe3 h4 {Several strong players reached this position while
representing either side. White generally tried Bxc6 and exd4 here.} 9. Bxc6+ (
9. exd4 {This is extremely dangerous.} Nxd4 10. e3 hxg3 11. hxg3 Nf5 $36 {
Black either gets a pawn back instantly or forces White to part with some
other material - say, an exchange.} 12. Rxf5 Bxf5 $17 {The fact that the game
lasted only 8 more moves should say a word or two about White's position. He's
not only material down, but also his position is nearly lost king safety-wise
and activity-wise. 0-1 (21) Gareyev,T (2569)-Morozevich,A (2656) St Petersburg
2018}) 9... bxc6 10. Qa4 hxg3 $5 $146 11. Qxc6+ Bd7 12. Qe4+ Be7 {Black stops
all the checks rather easily.} 13. hxg3 {At this point, we have a plethora of
choices. ...f7-f5, ... c7-c5, ...Rh3 and many other moves all look very decent!
} Rh3 $5 (13... f5 $5 $13) 14. Qg2 Bd6 15. Rf3 dxe3 $13 {This is a true mess,
but I think we can stop here - I would definitely think Black's position
should be rather easy to handle. All he needs is bring the knight and the
queen in the game.}) 5... Bb4+ {I believe this is the best way to meet White's
setup. The point of the check is that if White goes Nbd2, his development will
be disrupted as he might have wanted to instead either play Na3-c2, or let his
bishop come out to g5 in the first place. If Whie goes Bd2, his knight on b1
might not be able to get developed easily. Instead, Nfbd2 is typically the
right reaction.} 6. Nfd2 $1 {White keeps the possibility of Na3-c2 open.} (6.
Nbd2 a5 $1 {A very important move because we stop the threat of a2-a3, which
intends to either force the bishop trade on d2, or to meet the bishop retreat
with b2-b4! This is a standard pattern from the actual Benoni.} 7. O-O Nf6 8.
a3 Be7 {This is exactly something I was referring to in the intro as I was
explaining the merits of the check on b4. Now White cannot play Bg5 as the
knight is obstructing the way of the bishop, he cannot prepare b2-b4 as his
knight couldn't go to a3 and c2, and as a result, he just has NO plan
whatsoever.}) (6. Bd2 a5 7. O-O (7. Bxb4 axb4 {Now White opens the a-file for
us and creates a small weakness on a2, which shouldn't be too good.}) 7... Nf6
8. Na3 (8. a3 {This is a typical positional mistake in these lines as the
knight loses access to the route b1-a3-c2.} Be7 9. Bg5 O-O 10. Nbd2 a4 $15 {
Again, Black is already somewhat better. Instead of discussing specific moves,
we are much better off if we analyze some model games in this structure
carefully.}) 8... O-O 9. Nc2 Bc5 10. a3 a4 {We reach a typical Benoni-type
position where Black is definitely doing well. White does have some
counterplay, but we have nothing to worry about from the opening perspective.})
6... a5 $1 {As I explain in the annotations to 5.Nbd2, it's very important to
play this to stop a2-a3 and b2-b4.} 7. Na3 Nf6 8. Nc2 Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. b3 {
White intends to slowly prepare a2-a3, Rb1 and b3-b4 without allowing for
a2-a3 met by ...a5-a4!} (10. a3 $6 a4 $1 {It's very important to fix the
structure like this. Now b2-b3 will involve creation of a weakness on a3. Many
Benoni players like these positions, but they aren't too attractive from the
objective standpoint, for example} 11. b4 axb3 12. Nxb3 Na5 $1 13. Nxa5 Rxa5
14. Bd2 Ra7 15. a4 Bg4 {Black will follow up with ...c7-c6 to kill the
g2-bishop's pressure, ...Qd7, .. .Nd7-c5 etc, and it's not so easy for White
to create much play. He might be not much worse, or even nearly equal, but
this is clearly not the way you want the opening to go when you are White.})
10... Bg4 11. a3 Qd7 12. Rb1 {White keeps pursuing his plan.} Bh3 {We simply
trade the bishops.} 13. b4 (13. Bxh3 $2 Qxh3 14. b4 $4 Ng4 15. Nf3 f5 $19 {
...e5-e4 is inevitable and White should already resign.}) 13... axb4 14. axb4
Bxg2 15. Kxg2 b5 $1 {This is the key pattern you need to remember. The point
is that we immediately kill all of the White's play on the queenside. For
example, after} 16. cxb5 Na7 17. Na3 Nd5 $1 $15 {We can take advantage of the
newly-available d5-square and attack the b4-pawn as well as aim to land on
that lovely c3-square. White is just clearly worse.} *

