{[%evp 0,14,18,30,26,-3,12,-12,-12,9,9,9,15,-2,44,49,41]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3.
e3 Nc6 {This is known to be the simplest and the cleanest solution. At this
point, White will most likely take on d4, but 4.b4 is also possible. We will
analyze that continuation in the next file.} 4. exd4 Nxd4 5. Nxd4 Qxd4 6. d3 {
To start with 6.d3 is also possible, but White would need to play Nb1-c3
anyway soon. As you can guess, 6.Nc3 followed by d2-d3 is another way to get
here :)} (6. Nc3 c6 7. d3 Nh6 $1 {This seemingly ugly development of the
knight makes perfect sense. Why so? Because as you would imagine, White would
like to play Bc1-e3 and d3-d4, but then ...Nf5! would hit the White center
hard!} 8. Be3 Qd6 {We can also arrive here via a different move order - with 6.
d3 instead of 6.Nc3. We have analyzed the move 9.c5 there, let's now
concentrate on White's main move 9.d4.} 9. d4 Nf5 10. c5 (10. Qd2 Nxe3 $1 {
Now it doesn't matter how White captures, we are gonna play ...g7-g6 and ...
Bg7 or ...Bh6.} 11. Qxe3 g6 12. O-O-O {This isn't good, but at least it's
principled.} (12. c5 $6 Qe6 $1 {Is just a good way for White to get a slightly
worse position because of our bishop pair.}) 12... Bg7 {Now, I would like to
show what happens if White doesn't do anything and lets our initiative roll
freely.} 13. Be2 h5 $5 {A very cool move that creates an immediate threat of ..
.Bh6! Besides that, it prepares ...Bf5 and stops g2-g4.} 14. f4 (14. Bf3 $4 Bh6
$19) 14... Bf5 15. Rhf1 Rd8 $17 {[%csl Rc1,Rd4][%cal Gd8d4,Gg7d4,Gg7a1,Gf5b1]
This is exactly how White loses - I wanted to say "slowly but surely", but
here it's rather fast and surely.}) 10... Qe6 {This position is analyzed via
the move order 6.d3.}) 6... c6 7. Nc3 Nh6 {And we have transposed to the main
line.} 8. Be3 Qd6 $5 {This move is less frequent than ...Qd8, but I prefer to
keep my piece rather developed as opposed to undeveloping it purposefully. As
a side note, I'd like to mention it was chosen by several reputable GMs and
strong players, including a good friend of mine and a notable theoretician
Sergey Pavlov, whose opening choices I tend to trust and pay quite a bit of
attention to.} 9. c5 {The engine suggests this move at a low depth, and it was
played once by Goganov vs Sarana, but it looks highly committal. If White
doesn't get d4-d5 in, he might end up with several weak squares.} (9. d4 Nf5 {
We study this position via the 6.Nc3 move order.}) 9... Qe6 $146 {I like the
idea of creating the pin down the e-file.} 10. d4 Nf5 {We have actually
tranposed in the game Zakaryan-Pavlov. Now it makes no sense to just wait and
allow for ...Nxe3 followed by ...g7-g6 and ...Bh6, where White's position will
start falling apart.} 11. d5 (11. Qd2 {The game saw this move, and we'll
analyze it via a different move order in the main line. 0-1 (35) Zakaryan,D 
(2378)-Pavlov,S (2481) Moscow 2019} Nxe3 $1 $146 12. fxe3 (12. Qxe3 Qxe3+ 13.
fxe3 g6 $15 {Black's bishop pair is definitely going to tell in the long run.})
12... g6 $17 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gf8h6,Gh6d2]}) 11... Nxe3 $5 {The most
straightforward continuation.} 12. dxe6 Nxd1 13. exf7+ Kxf7 14. Rxd1 Be6 $11 {
We can boast of the bishop pair and are certainly no worse as ... g7-g6 and ...
Bg7 are on the way.} *

