{[%evp 0,14,31,21,20,-13,8,9,9,0,3,-18,10,-28,-6,-13,-2]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3.
e3 Nc6 4. b4 {This is a very ambitious way to continue - White is playing the
Blumenfeld gambit with colours reversed, or nearly so - in that line, Black
would typically have the moves ...Nf6 and ...c7-c5 made instead of ...Nc6.
White is claiming he is ready to sacrifice a pawn in order to get the massive
center and plenty of active play. While this is not a frequent continuation, I
think it's a rather serious idea that needs to be analyzed very carefully, as
White's compensation might be rather dangerous in practical settings.} dxe3 {
We are rather forced to accept the challenge.} (4... Nxb4 {Is also possible
and leads to a fairly intereresting position. White can capture on d4 with
either piece, or give a check.} 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. Nxd4 Bd7 7. Nxc6 Bxc6 8. Qc2 {
Everything has been quite forced up to now.} e5 $13 {Black reaches a decent
position here, objectively. So, this is a side option you might want to
consider in the event if my main recommendation does not appeal all that much
to you, or if you are simply looking for a very easy solution, as White's
options are quite limited here. Yet, I feel we haven't been principled enough
- objectively, this whole thing together with 4.b4 isn't the best way to play
chess, so we should try to fight for the advantage!}) 5. fxe3 (5. dxe3 $2 {
Of course, this is rubbish.} Qxd1+ 6. Kxd1 Nxb4 $19 {Black is just totally
winning.}) 5... Nxb4 {We reach a rather popular position that has been seen in
more than 150 games. Almost everyone chose to play 6.d4 here, but we will also
look at 6.Qa4 and 6.Nc3.} 6. d4 {White immediately grabs the center - makes
sense!} (6. Qa4+ Nc6 7. d4 Bd7 {The bishop looks weird here, but in fact, after
} 8. Qb3 Na5 $1 {Black's position is very stable. Now the typical plan is} 9.
Qc2 c5 $1 10. d5 Nf6 11. e4 e5 $1 {The goal is to reach the stable blockade
after ...Bd6, while if White takes, the position opens to our favor.} 12. Nxe5
Bd6 13. Nxd7 Nxd7 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Gd7e5,Gd6e5,Re5a1,Rd8h4] Black completely
owns the dark squares, and all the kitchen sink is about to be thrown at White.
...Qh4+, ...Ne5, ...Be5 are all very unpleasant moves that are up and coming
and are about to show how dominant we are on the dark squares.}) (6. Nc3 c5 {
Again, it seems very natural to take control over the center.} 7. d4 g6 {
We could take, but it makes sense to just develop. Again, the goal is just to
continue with ...Bg7, ...Nf6, ...O-O, etc, finally establishing firm control
over the long diagonal and the dark squares. This is a brand-new position so
we won't go any farther, let's just agree we follow the plans shown elsewhere
in the chapter.}) 6... e5 $1 {This is the most popular solution, and for a
good reason. Black can try to instead hold on to his extra pawn, but then
White gets exactly what he wants - a powerful center and plenty of active play.
Instead, the concept of returning the extra material to stabilize the position
and to ensure decent counterplay sounds way more appealing to me. Hands down.}
7. a3 {This is what people mostly did as White, but I cannot say I like this
move too much for Whie, as now the knight is very stable on c6. And, it allows
for additional simplifications.} (7. Nxe5 {This is the better move objectively,
in my opinion. But, it doesn't lead to any fun for White.} Bf5 $146 (7... Qh4+
{Is also possible, and this is what people also did. But I like my suggestion
even better.}) 8. Na3 {The knight has to go here. But a very typical situation
arises now, when the b4-knight is rather annoying and because the White knight
is on a3, there is no way to kick this knight away with a2-a3. Instead, moving
the a3-knight to prepare a2-a3 isn't possible, either.} Bd6 {Now White needs
to either allow for ...Bxe5, which clearly isn't a fun structure for him, or
he should retreat with the knight.} 9. Be2 (9. Nf3 c5 $1 {We immediately
tackle the center.} 10. Be2 Nf6 11. O-O O-O $15 {Black is again much better
because the e4-square and the e3-pawn are so weak. The a3-knight doesn't make
White's position any beautiful, either.}) 9... Bxe5 10. dxe5 $2 (10. O-O $3 {
This is an insane engine suggestion, but after} Ne7 {The f5-bishop is
protected again and White finally has to take.} 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 a6 $1 {
The last precise move, dealing with Nb5-related ideas. Black's advantage may
not be huge, but it's very long-lasting and annoying.}) 10... Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1
O-O-O+ $19 {Black's initiative is just crushing.}) 7... Nc6 (7... e4 $5 {
This is a bit less ambitious, but also very decent.} 8. Nfd2 Nd3+ 9. Bxd3 exd3
{Now, in a nutshell, what's gonna happen is that White will regain his pawn
while Black will develop quickly. White gets the center and the open f-file,
while we enjoy the bishop pair - the situation is balanced, so if you want to
cut down on the amount of theory you need to study, feel free to pick this
line!} 10. O-O Nf6 11. Nf3 Bf5 12. Nc3 Be7 13. Ne5 Bg6 14. Ra2 Bd6 15. Nxd3 O-O
{The position was between equality and Black's slight advantage and later he
went on to win, which is a good sign, but just as any possible outcome of the
game, should not influence the way we evaluate the position. 0-1 (45) Galyas,M
(2459)-Bacrot,E (2697) Caleta 2016}) 8. Nc3 (8. d5 {At this point, Black has
several good solutions, but I like the most straightforward} e4 $1 9. dxc6 (9.
Nfd2 Ne5 10. Nxe4 Qh4+ 11. Nf2 Bc5 $17 {Is just a terrible opening outcome for
White who is getting kicked all around the place.}) 9... Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 exf3
11. gxf3 b6 $5 {The c-pawn is weak and Black hopes to pick it later, he is
better.} (11... bxc6 $15 {This looks like a free pawn to me. Things look good,
we are just better!})) 8... Nf6 9. d5 (9. Be2 {Now we are ready to release the
tension in the center.} exd4 10. exd4 Be7 11. O-O O-O {To be fair enough, we
need to say White does some compensation, but to me, the extra pawn clearly
looks more valuable. We are just better.}) 9... Ne7 $5 $146 {The knight is
getting re-rerouted to a new excellent spot.} 10. Nxe5 Ng6 11. Nf3 Bd6 12. Bd3
O-O 13. O-O Qe7 $17 {Black has a clear strategic advantage thanks to the
outposts on e5 and c5 and due to the fact White's e-pawn is rather weak.} *

