{[%evp 0,5,19,30,30,-16,0,14]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. b4 $1 {This is definitely
the most critical continuation - both in this position and in this database,
overall. To be honest, I was somewhat puzzled what continuation to suggest, as
I have analyzed several of them for my own purposes. Black's choices vary from
the classic 3...f6 or 3...c5 to such oddities as 3...g5!?!? - too many signs
to show that the move is both ingenious and dubious! It is also perfectly
possible to continue with 3...Bg4, 3...Nf6, 3...a5, 3...g6 and many other
moves. So, what choice did I go for?!} Bg4 $5 {I find this rather rare
continuation to be solid and reputable enough to be recommended, and, very
importantly, very easy to play. Black avoids all those crazy lines which arise
after 3...f6 and aims for positional play. Now, White typically goes 4.Qb3 -
that's the move we will consider in the next chapter. But, he had also tried
several other possibilities, and that's exactly what we will be covering here.}
4. Ne5 {Several good players aimed for this move. At this point, I would like
to go somewhat wild with} (4. Bb2 {This gives us a chance to demonstrate our
idea.} Bxf3 5. exf3 e5 {[%csl Rb2,Rf1] White's b2-bishop clearly doesn't look
too good at the moment. For example, after} 6. a3 a5 $1 7. c5 $1 {This is the
way to go, enabling the bishop on f1 to come out to c4.} (7. b5 $2 Nd7 $15 {
Black is clearly better thanks to the c5-square.}) 7... Nf6 8. Bc4 Be7 9. O-O
O-O 10. Re1 axb4 11. axb4 Rxa1 12. Bxa1 b6 $1 {Instead of protecting the
e5-pawn, Black dismantles opponent's pawn chain.} 13. cxb6 (13. Rxe5 bxc5 14.
bxc5 Nbd7 15. Re2 Bxc5 $11 {This position should be nearly drawn. Now it's
roughly balanced, but I'd imagine, it would be rather difficult to win with
either side. Well, that's the objective truth and the way chess is - you
cannot hope to win by force with Black or something!}) 13... cxb6 14. b5 Nbd7
$11 {The players have reached another balanced position where Black can boast
of an outpost on c5 and of the fact that the White a1-bishop clearly isn't too
impressive - this is an interesting position to play out. Later, skill/luck
turned the tables to Black's favor. 0-1 (76) Kalka,A (2334)-Khenkin,I (2565)
Germany 2016}) (4. d3 {This move has the same problem as 4.Bb2 - it just
allows us to take.} Bxf3 $1 5. exf3 e5 {Again, the b4-pawn is hanging.} 6. b5 (
6. a3 a5 {Is pretty much the same thing.}) 6... Bb4+ $1 {I like this check as
it disrupts White's development a little bit.} 7. Bd2 (7. Nd2 $6 a6 $1 {
Black immediately stars undermining the overextended queenside of his opponent
- this seems unpleasant.}) 7... Bxd2+ 8. Nxd2 Nf6 $146 9. g3 Nbd7 10. Bg2 Nc5
11. O-O O-O $132 {We reach a roughly balanced position where both sides
definitely have their chances. Without one pair of knights, I'd call this a
massive advantage for Black, as the monster on c5 is clearly more useful than
the White bishop. The present position is roughly balanced, but I think
White's task is more difficult as he might need to play dynamically, which
would possibly some pawn sacrifices like f3-f4.}) (4. Qa4+ {That's also a
possibility, which we calmly meet with} c6 {Now after any White move - say, 5.
Ne5, 5.Bb2 or 5.d3 we will continue in the same way as we would after the same
moves on move 4.}) 4... h5 $5 {This move was played in one game only between
two players below 2000, so it's almost a novelty. The idea is to provoke White
to take on g4 and to get a very nasty pawn on g4 that will be squeezing the
White kingside. The h-file will open, too, which would be quite inconvenient
for White. Please pay attention to the fact that this position is an exact
copy of the line in Trompowsky with colors reversed which arises after 1.d4
Nf6 2.Bg5 c5 3.d5 Ne4 4.h4 with the only difference that White has a move
b2-b4 in for free. The good thing is that this fact stops him from playing Qb3,
attacking the b7-pawn. The principled Nxg4 positions need to be considered now.
White can definitely delay the capture, but it's more or less going to
transpose as ...Nd7 is about to be played and White would need to take.} (4...
Bf5 {Is also possible and has a good reputation, so check it out if you're
looking for a more solid way to continue!}) 5. Nxg4 hxg4 6. g3 Nd7 7. Bg2 e5 $5
{We don't care about the b7-pawn as ...Rb8 will easily restore the material
balance.} 8. b5 (8. d3 $2 Bxb4+ {White doesn't want to hang the pawn!}) 8...
Nc5 9. d3 f5 10. Nd2 (10. O-O $2 Qf6 $17 {...Qg6-h5, ...f5-f4 and long
castling will quickly lead White to lots of trouble. He's already experiencing
serious issues.}) 10... Qd7 $1 (10... Nf6 $5 11. Nb3 $1 {It's crucial to trade
the beautiful c5-knight. The reason why I am not recommending this is because
Black either needs to play the weird ...Rb8 move, or sacrifice the b7-pawn.
The engine believes both are completely fine, but this seems too odd to me.})
11. Nb3 O-O-O {Black doesn't fear the fact that the g2-bishop has such a long
diagonal at his disposal as he's about to shut it down soon.} 12. a4 Nf6 13. a5
e4 $1 {We reach some fairly crazy position where I already believe Black is
just better.} *

