{[%evp 0,22,19,24,35,-5,24,14,40,-23,39,-22,9,-6,50,-27,0,-7,0,-12,-23,-23,1,1,
11]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. b4 Bg4 4. Qb3 {This is the main line after 3...Bg4
and a real test of our setup. White prepares to meet ...Bxf3 with Qxf3,
avoiding the spoiled structure. The ultimate reason why I decided to recommend
3...Bg4 is because I believe I have found a very serious and new idea, which
serves as a perfect antidote to this 4.Qb3 line.} a5 $1 {Now we end up in a
position where only 9(!) games have been played. Man, 9 games after 4 moves
only, I wish we could get this creative more frequently! Of course, at this
point, White has a choice. Most players - and for a good reason - continued 5.
b5. But one GM-level game saw 5.Ne5 and that's something we need to consider
seriously as well.} 5. b5 (5. Ne5 Bc8 $5 {A really strange position, isn't
it?! The strategic achievement is that White cannot play a2-a3 as the a1-rook
is unprotected. So, he needs to close the position with b4-b5, thus limiting
his potential on the queenside.} 6. b5 f6 7. Nf3 e5 $132 {Again, it's possible
to go deeper, but I like Black who has grabbed tons of space and is about to
simply continue with the natural developing moves - we cannot have any
problems here.}) 5... a4 $5 {We prevent a2-a4 and grab space on the queenside.}
6. Qd3 {This is a somewhat odd-looking move, but it fact, it makes perfect
sense as it still keeps an eye on the f3-knight, making ...Bxf3 pointless. At
the same time, White's attacking the d4-pawn.} (6. Qc2 $146 {At this point, a
few continuations are perfectly okay, but the most logical clearly is} Bxf3 $1
7. exf3 e6 {We will continue in a very similar manner to the positions we
discuss in the file devoted to sidelines on move 4, where White allows for
this structure. A simple maneuvre to mention is ...Nd7-c5, making use of the
wonderful outpost. Besides that, Black just intends to develop, keep the
position closed and slowly outplay White. Obviously, it's a balanced situation,
but we have nothing to worry about.}) 6... c5 $1 {I don't want to give up my
bishop, so we are just protecting the d4-pawn. Now we have a really weird
position where White seems to have many choices, but in reality, there's only
one or two setups that could possibly arise.} 7. g3 {If White simply develops,
we'll answer in the same way.} (7. bxc6 $2 Nxc6 $17 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gf7f5] Now
that the position opens up, White's queen proves really misplaced on d3. The
simple ...e7-e5 and ...Nf6 should immediately yield us the nearly decisive
advantage.} 8. e3 $2 Nb4 {[%csl Rc2]} 9. Qe4 Nf6 $19) (7. Qe4 {Of course, this
looks like a strange move, but it's a double attack on the bishop and the
b7-pawn, so we need to take it seriously.} Bc8 $5 {This is an attempt to play
for a win. You will continue with ...Nf6, ...g7-g6, ...Bg7 etc. Feel free to
study this position deeper yourself as 7...Nf6 is a forced draw, at least -
there's no need to look for a forced win out of the opening with the Black
pieces, we need to stop at some point!} (7... Nf6 8. Qxb7 Nbd7 {Is an
immediate draw, because White cannot escape with his queen and the ...Rb8 Qa7
Ra8 repetition is inevitable here. I mean, only Black can choose to deviate,
but not White, so we already have a draw in the pocket.})) (7. Ne5 Bc8 {
Again, this bishop's travel all over the board might seem strange, but we
achieved a few important strategic goals, such as stopping all of White's
potential play on the queenside and misplacing his queen. So, there's no need
to worry, as we are about to just continue with ...f7-f6 and ...e7-e5.} 8. e3
f6 9. Nf3 e5 {We will just develop the kingside and castle with a fantastic
game.}) 7... Nd7 8. Bg2 e5 9. Qc2 h6 $5 {A very nice prophylactical move which
prevents such ideas as h2-h3, intending to meet ...Be6 with Ng5.} 10. d3 Bd6
11. O-O Ne7 $15 {White has no play on the queenside, while e2-e3 isn't a big
deal - we will keep a slight advantage anyway due to our extra space.} *

