{[#] What maneuvre do I suggest for Black here?} 10... Nc6 $1 {A slightly
unconventional square for the knight. The idea is revealed soon.} 11. Nd2 Ne7
$1 12. Nf3 Nf5 $1 {The knight is placed extremely solidly on f5, but if needed,
it can come to d6 and to e4, or to d6 and just stay there, controlling the c4
and e4-squares. Later, we can prepare . .. a7-a5-a4, initiating some play on
the queenside. It's crucial that both of the White bishops are rather passive
and useless. We won't even open up the game too much, and we'll meet c2-c4
with ...c7-c6, leaving White wondering how to make use of his bishops. One
interesting plan could involve moving the f8-rook somewhere and playing ...Bf8,
possibly supporting the ...a7-a5-a4 plan. Black is doing just great here.
Please take a look at the chapter on 2.b3 3.Bb2.} *

