{[#] This is just a tiny memory marker. White just played d2-d3, what do we do?
} 5... Bb4+ $1 {This check is crucial for the sake of disrupting White's
development. Other moves are also possible, but in order to stay within the
boundaries of this repertoire, we need to give this check. Please note we meet
O-O instead of d2-d3 with the aggressive ...e5-e4! followed by ...h7-h5! -
make sure to repeat this in the chapter on 2.c4 d4 3.g3.} 6. Nfd2 $1 (6. Nbd2
$6 a5 $1 {A very important move because we stop the threat of a2-a3, which
intends to either force the bishop trade on d2, or to meet the bishop retreat
with b2-b4! This is a standard pattern from the actual Benoni.}) 6... a5 $1 {
As I explain in the annotations to 5.Nbd2, it's very important to play this to
stop a2-a3 and b2-b4.} 7. Na3 Nf6 8. Nc2 Bd6 {We analyze this position in a
lot more detail in the chapter on 2.c4 3.g3.} *

